Supervised Learning - Foundations: ReCell¶

Marks: 60

Context¶

Buying and selling used phones and tablets used to be something that happened on a handful of online marketplace sites. But the used and refurbished device market has grown considerably over the past decade, and a new IDC (International Data Corporation) forecast predicts that the used phone market would be worth \$52.7bn by 2023 with a compound annual growth rate (CAGR) of 13.6% from 2018 to 2023. This growth can be attributed to an uptick in demand for used phones and tablets that offer considerable savings compared with new models.

Refurbished and used devices continue to provide cost-effective alternatives to both consumers and businesses that are looking to save money when purchasing one. There are plenty of other benefits associated with the used device market. Used and refurbished devices can be sold with warranties and can also be insured with proof of purchase. Third-party vendors/platforms, such as Verizon, Amazon, etc., provide attractive offers to customers for refurbished devices. Maximizing the longevity of devices through second-hand trade also reduces their environmental impact and helps in recycling and reducing waste. The impact of the COVID-19 outbreak may further boost this segment as consumers cut back on discretionary spending and buy phones and tablets only for immediate needs.

Objective¶

The rising potential of this comparatively under-the-radar market fuels the need for an ML-based solution to develop a dynamic pricing strategy for used and refurbished devices. ReCell, a startup aiming to tap the potential in this market, has hired you as a data scientist. They want you to analyze the data provided and build a linear regression model to predict the price of a used phone/tablet and identify factors that significantly influence it.

Data Description¶

The data contains the different attributes of used/refurbished phones and tablets. The detailed data dictionary is given below.

Data Dictionary

  • brand_name: Name of manufacturing brand
  • os: OS on which the device runs
  • screen_size: Size of the screen in cm
  • 4g: Whether 4G is available or not
  • 5g: Whether 5G is available or not
  • main_camera_mp: Resolution of the rear camera in megapixels
  • selfie_camera_mp: Resolution of the front camera in megapixels
  • int_memory: Amount of internal memory (ROM) in GB
  • ram: Amount of RAM in GB
  • battery: Energy capacity of the device battery in mAh
  • weight: Weight of the device in grams
  • release_year: Year when the device model was released
  • days_used: Number of days the used/refurbished device has been used
  • new_price: Price of a new device of the same model in euros
  • used_price: Price of the used/refurbished device in euros

Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA)¶

  • EDA is an important part of any project involving data.
  • It is important to investigate and understand the data better before building a model with it.
  • A few questions have been mentioned below which will help you approach the analysis in the right manner and generate insights from the data.
  • A thorough analysis of the data, in addition to the questions mentioned below, should be done.

Questions:

  1. What does the distribution of used device prices look like?
  2. What percentage of the used device market is dominated by Android devices?
  3. The amount of RAM is important for the smooth functioning of a device. How does the amount of RAM vary with the brand?
  4. A large battery often increases a device's weight, making it feel uncomfortable in the hands. How does the weight vary for phones and tablets offering large batteries (more than mAh)?
  5. Bigger screens are desirable for entertainment purposes as they offer a better viewing experience. How many phones and tablets are available across different brands with a screen size larger than 6 inches?
  6. Budget devices nowadays offer great selfie cameras, allowing us to capture our favorite moments with loved ones. What is the distribution of budget devices offering greater than 8MP selfie cameras across brands?
  7. Which attributes are highly correlated with the price of a used device?

# function to plot a boxplot and a histogram along the same scale.


def histogram_boxplot(data, feature, figsize=(12, 7), kde=False, bins=None):
    """
    Boxplot and histogram combined

    data: dataframe
    feature: dataframe column
    figsize: size of figure (default (12,7))
    kde: whether to the show density curve (default False)
    bins: number of bins for histogram (default None)
    """
    f2, (ax_box2, ax_hist2) = plt.subplots(
        nrows=2,  # Number of rows of the subplot grid= 2
        sharex=True,  # x-axis will be shared among all subplots
        gridspec_kw={"height_ratios": (0.25, 0.75)},
        figsize=figsize,
    )  # creating the 2 subplots
    sns.boxplot(
        data=data, x=feature, ax=ax_box2, showmeans=True, color="violet"
    )  # boxplot will be created and a star will indicate the mean value of the column
    sns.histplot(
        data=data, x=feature, kde=kde, ax=ax_hist2, bins=bins, palette="winter"
    ) if bins else sns.histplot(
        data=data, x=feature, kde=kde, ax=ax_hist2
    )  # For histogram
    ax_hist2.axvline(
        data[feature].mean(), color="green", linestyle="--"
    )  # Add mean to the histogram
    ax_hist2.axvline(
        data[feature].median(), color="black", linestyle="-"
    )  # Add median to the histogram

# function to create labeled barplots


def labeled_barplot(data, feature, perc=False, n=None):
    """
    Barplot with percentage at the top

    data: dataframe
    feature: dataframe column
    perc: whether to display percentages instead of count (default is False)
    n: displays the top n category levels (default is None, i.e., display all levels)
    """

    total = len(data[feature])  # length of the column
    count = data[feature].nunique()
    if n is None:
        plt.figure(figsize=(count + 1, 5))
    else:
        plt.figure(figsize=(n + 1, 5))

    plt.xticks(rotation=90, fontsize=15)
    ax = sns.countplot(
        data=data,
        x=feature,
        palette="Paired",
        order=data[feature].value_counts().index[:n].sort_values(),
    )

    for p in ax.patches:
        if perc == True:
            label = "{:.1f}%".format(
                100 * p.get_height() / total
            )  # percentage of each class of the category
        else:
            label = p.get_height()  # count of each level of the category

        x = p.get_x() + p.get_width() / 2  # width of the plot
        y = p.get_height()  # height of the plot

        ax.annotate(
            label,
            (x, y),
            ha="center",
            va="center",
            size=12,
            xytext=(0, 5),
            textcoords="offset points",
        )  # annotate the percentage

    plt.show()  # show the plot

Missing value treatment¶

  • 'main_camera_mp', 'selfie_camera_mp', 'battery', 'internal memory', and 'weight' have skewed distribution, we will fill the NaN with median.
  • 'ram' has quite normal distribution, we will fill the NaN with mean.
In [54]:
# to create a new dataframe from df so we would not make changes on the df file.
df1 = df.copy()
df1["main_camera_mp"].fillna(
    df1.main_camera_mp.median(), inplace=True
)  # to replace NaN with median
df1["selfie_camera_mp"].fillna(
    df1.selfie_camera_mp.median(), inplace=True
)  # to replace rows with median
df1["int_memory"].fillna(
    df1.int_memory.median(), inplace=True
)  # to replace NaN with median
df1["ram"].fillna(df1.ram.mean(), inplace=True)  # to replace NaN with mean
df1["battery"].fillna(df1.battery.median(), inplace=True)  # to replace NaN with median
df1["weight"].fillna(df1.weight.median(), inplace=True)  # to replace NaN with median

# To perfrom log transformation for all columns in cols_to_log in df1 dataframe
for colname in cols_to_log:
    df1[colname + "_log"] = np.log(
        df1[colname] + 1
    )  # +1 to make sure we can perfrom lof transformation for column(s) that has 0 in it.

)  # inplace= True means the dataframe is now updated

Checking Linear Regression Assumptions¶

  • In order to make statistical inferences from a linear regression model, it is important to ensure that the assumptions of linear regression are satisfied.

For Linear Regression, we need to check if the following assumptions hold:-

  1. Linearity
  2. Independence
  3. Homoscedasticity
  4. Normality of error terms
  5. No strong Multicollinearity

Checking Linearity¶

In [83]:
import pandas as pd

df_pred = pd.DataFrame()

df_pred["Actual Values"] = y_train.values.flatten()  # actual values
df_pred["Fitted Values"] = olsres_5.fittedvalues.values  # predicted values
df_pred["Residuals"] = olsres_5.resid.values  # residuals

Test for Homoscedasity¶

In [87]:
# to import a package
import statsmodels.stats.api as sms
from statsmodels.compat import lzip

The null and alternate hypotheses of the goldfeldquandt test are as follows:

  • Null hypothesis : Residuals are homoscedastic
  • Alternate hypothesis : Residuals have hetroscedasticity
In [88]:
# to chech the p-value for residules
name = ["F statistic", "p-value"]
test = sms.het_goldfeldquandt(df_pred["Residuals"], x_train)
lzip(name, test)
Out[88]:
[('F statistic', 1.085908892708136), ('p-value', 0.07738650909206692)]
  • Since p-value > 0.05 we can say that the residuals are homoscedastic.

All the assumptions of linear regression are now satisfied.

Observations¶

  • R-squared of the model is 0.844 and adjusted R-squared is 0.843, which shows that the model is able to explain ~84% variance in the data. This is quite good.

  • A unit increase in the weight will result in a 0.4618 unit increase in the used price, all other variables remaining constant.

  • A unit increase in the new price will result in a 0.3654 unit increase in the used price, all other variables remaining constant.

  • The Window os will be 0.0202 units higher than a device with the Android os, all other variables remaining constant.

  • The iOS os will be 0.0673 units lower than a device with the Android os, all other variables remaining constant.

  • The medium price range (251-500 dollars) device will be 0.2917 units higher than a budget price range (0-250 dollars) device, all other variables remaining constant.

  • The premium price range (501-750 dollars) device will be 0.5915 units higher than a budget price range (0-250 dollars) device, all other variables remaining constant.

Actionable Insights and Recommendations¶

  • The data set has 3454 observations and 15 columns.
  • The final liniear regression model has:
    • R-squared 0.844 and adjusted R-squared 0.843, which shows that the model is able to explain ~84% variance in the data. This is quite good.
    • RMSE on the train (0.2264) and test (0.2281) sets are comparable. Therefore, the model is not suffering from overfitting or noices.
    • The model is able to predict used price within a mean error of 0.18 units on the test data.
    • In conclusion, the final liniear regression model is good for prediction and inference purposes.
  • From the model, the significant predictors, in order, to predict a price of used phone/tablet are:
    • Type of the device: budget, medium, or premium devices based on resale prices. Premium devices would have higher resale prices.
      • OnePlus has the highest median of used price 183 dollars, follow by Apple 172 dollars, and Google 138 dollars.
    • The weight of the device. The heavy the device, the higher price.
      • For devices to have great functionality, they would come with good camera, larger screen, good battery size, etc. These parts would cause the devices to weight more than devices with less functionality.
      • From the graph between resale price and weight of devices, there are two patterns that weight has possitive impact in resale price.
      • It's possible that one pattern is for cellphones and another for tables.
    • The price of the device if buy new, the higher, the better.
      • The price of a new device usually indicates the demand of the product.
      • Therefore, the demand for pre-owned products effects the resale price of those products as well.
  • The features below have some influence but not as significant
    • The resolution of main (0.0 - 48 MP) camera and selfie camera (0.0 - 32 MP), the higher, the better.
      • More and more, consumers use cellphone for pictures and video instead of using a camera. The demand of a quality resolution of a phone/tablet has increase.
      • For the main camera, the resolution 48 MP has the highest resale price at 233 dollars
      • However, the resolution 9 MP of selfie cacmera has the highest resale price at 271 dollars.
      • From the data, it indicates that consumers prefer the highest resolution of main camera but prefers a lower resolution for selfie.
    • RAM, the higher, the better.
    • Internal memory, the higer, the better.
      • The internal memory of 1024 GB has the highest resale price, follow by 256 GB and 128 GB rather than 512 GB.
      • It indicates that 512 GB of internal memory is not fit with the demand from consumers whom need larger memory space for heavier usage but too much for another group whom need less memory space for ligher usage.
    • Battery size, the higer, the better.
      • Bigger battery size, the more power to run more programs on device and last longer before it needs to be charged.
    • Operation System, Windows has a higer impact on resale price.
      • From the data set, Andriod has the most amount at 3214 units, followed by others 137 units, Windows 67 units, and iOS 36 units.
      • iOS operation system has the highest median price 138 dollars and followed by Android 83 dollars, Windows 56 dollars, and others 26 dollars.
      • The contract from the model and the data indicates that although there are demands of Windows and iOs, however, Andriod devices have the largest market market share.
    • 4g (fourth-generation wireless), the stage of broadband mobile communications has more impact on resale price than 5g.
      • However, 5g devices have a higher reseal price.
      • there are 4.4% of devices with 5g and 67.6% with 4g.
      • With this data set, more than half of devices were produced in 2013-2015, 5g devices were not widely accessable.
      • This indicates that there are a high demand for 5g devices.
      • With the technology advancing rapidly, it would be a fair prediction that 5g would be another influent feature for the resale market.
